    "verbatimText": "First line below the search box:\nGlobal / Travel / Things to Do When Your Retire / Semester Abroad\n\nPuberty Rites Encounter\n3.5 stars (1 review)   No cancellation   Unknown\nDuration\n2 hours\nCancellation\nIt\u2019s only for you, so you have to go and participate\nMobile ticket\nNot a ticketed event\nLanguage\nKrobo (a dialect of the Dangme language), some Twi\nOverview\nThe Dipo Festival is celebrated by the Odumase Krobo in Ghana\u2019s Eastern Region and was traditionally held for girls who had reached puberty and were of marriageable age, typically thirteen to sixteen. To participate, the girl must be a virgin. As part of the ceremony, the young girl sits on a sacred stone. If she is not a virgin, legend has it, she\u2019ll get stuck. \n\nSupporters of the ceremony describe Dipo as a rite of passage that teaches girls about domestic life, sexual health, and marriage. Critics point to its rigid gender roles and fixation on virginity. Recently, this has become a practical problem. As one local newspaper headline bluntly put it: \u201cLack of virgins frustrates Dipo rites.\u201d Two workarounds have emerged: allowing younger girls, some as young as four, and allowing sexually active girls who have not given birth.\n\nPrior to the Dipo Festival, usually held in April, the girls practice, and you can attend a practice. \n\nWhy travelers book it\n\t\u2022\tThey want an authentic cultural experience.\n\t\u2022\tThe Akwasidae Festival in Kumasi takes place only once every six weeks and does not align with their travel dates.\n\t\u2022\tThe animal safari options in Ghana are not as strong as those in Kenya, Tanzania, South Africa, Botswana, and most other African countries.\n\t\u2022\tGhana is a relatively stable democracy, but short on tourist infrastructure and activities.\n\nGood to know\n\t\u2022\tThe performance will be totally fake, staged just for you.\n\t\u2022\tYou may meet Ms. Black USA at the recycled glass bead workshop, and your guide will convince her to join you at the staged ceremony.\n\t\u2022\tThe girls will wear exquisite recycled-glass beaded necklaces.\n\t\u2022\tThe necklaces are heavy, which you will experience when you join in their dance.\n\t\u2022\tTaking and giving away photos with an instant camera will increase your popularity, but not as much as being Ms. Black USA.\nWhat\u2019s Included\n\t\u2022\tThree outfitted dancers, musicians, a singer, a sound system, tent and decorations, plastic chairs, and attendance by the village\n\t\u2022\tVideo footage of you joining the girls in their dance\n\t\u2022\tSwig of unknown liquor from an unlabeled bottle shared by the village chief\n\t\u2022\tKnowledge you made a sizeable financial contribution to the village\n\nNot included\n\t\u2022\tExplanation of the meaning of the many beaded necklaces\n\t\u2022\tExplanation of the meaning of the markings on the girls\u2019 arms, backs, and chest\n\t\u2022\tExplanation of the dance\n\t\u2022\tExplanation of the Dipo ceremony\n\nDetails\nMeeting Point  Odumase Krobo, Ghana, whenever you arrive it starts\nEnding Point    Ends whenever you are done\nAccessibility     Ability to join in the dancing is appreciated, but not required\nWhat to bring    Instant camera, the physical photos will be a hit\n\nReviews\n3.5 stars (1)   Only line is 3.5 stars\nMargo W March 2024\nAuthentically Fake\nI felt pressured to take a swig out of that bottle. I knocked off a star for that. I would have liked some sort of explanation of what the hell was going on. Knocked of \u00bd star for that. But, on reflection, I no longer care that the entire \u201cceremony\u201d was been put on for me. The ceremony might have been fake, but the experience was real. I met a community in a small Ghanian village and got a glimpse into their traditional culture. Through my tourism dollars, I contributed financially to the community. And I made connections. I know those photos will last, though they\u2019ll probably fade before my memories. "
